STAFF WRITER THE Zimbabwe National Road Administration (Zinara) is now pegging toll fees in both US$ and the local currency, effectively increasing the amount that motorists have to pay for light vehicles from about $120 to about $165 at the prevailing foreign currency auction rate. This follows a December 2020 application by Zinara to Treasury for temporary exemption to allow motorists to pay in United States dollars in a bid to ease congestion at toll gates during the festive season. The ministry of Transport made the announcement in a Government Gazette yesterday that light motor vehicles would now pay US$2 ($165) while minibuses will pay US$3 ($247), buses  US$4 ($330), heavy vehicles  US$5 ($330) and haulage trucks US$ 10 ($826) to pass through a tollgate. “Toll fees for foreign-registered vehicles shall be payable in United States dollars or equivalent in other foreign currencies… “The fees stipulated above may be payable in local currency at the foreign currency auction rate in terms of the exchange control; exclusive use of Zimbabwe dollar for domestic transactions, (Amendment) Regulations, 2020, published in Statutory Instrument 185 of 2020,” the gazette read. The new toll fees are with immediate effect. Zinara made the application to the Treasury for the green light to use the greenback through their parent ministry, the ministry of Transport and Infrastructure Development. The current tolling fees for light motor vehicles that fall under class one are at $120 while class two vehicles are at $180. Sponsored Links

    
      
        
          
